SIMPLE: fleece
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fleece
<hw>Fleece</hw> <pr>(fl⟦emac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flees</ets>, AS. <ets>fle⟦oacute⟧s</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>flies</ets>, <ets>vlies</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The entire
coat of wool that covers a sheep or other similar animal; also, the
quantity shorn from a sheep, or animal, at one time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who shore me⟦br⟧
Like a tame wether, all my precious <qex>fleece</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any soft woolly covering resembling a
fleece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Manuf.)</fld> <def>The fine web of cotton or wool
removed by the doffing knife from the cylinder of a carding
machine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fleece wool</b></col>, <cd>wool shorn from the
sheep.</cd> -- <col><b>Golden fleece</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Golden</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleece</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fleece
<hw>Fleece</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fleeced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fleecing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To deprive of a
fleece, or natural covering of wool.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strip of money or other property unjustly,
especially by trickery or fraud; to bring to straits by oppressions and
exactions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whilst pope and prince shared the wool betwixt them, the people
were finely <qex>fleeced</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spread over as with wool.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleeced</ent>⟦br⟧
